This is the price, which he must pay for reaching his dream.
“I will work here still two years, because I open a shop or”, promises he would like to learn Spanish or French in one more than only acceptable English.
This pleasant and intelligent, but young man punished by the life could work as a tourist leader, waiter or on the receipt of a hotel, but instead he performs the work of a carrying donkey.
It divides a dirty cabin with other carriers and rises each morning at two o'clock, because the sulfur leaks out also at night, where its characteristic yellow color in the darkness shines bluish.
The shade provocatively, he rises in the light of a small head lamp at his helmet, which he bought from his own money, into the crater.
Approximately 400 carriers load themselves at the crater ground the baskets with sulfur on their shoulders.
Despite its large profits the mine company did not mechanize the sulfur dismantling, in order to save costs, and supplies with to the carriers, which work on own bill and are paid after weight, no equipment.
They receive also no portion of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) to addition per camera, which the guards of this nature park as well as the admission fee at a value of 15.000 rupees (1.2 euros) require of the tourists, who come to photographing the volcano and the human carrying donkeys.
“This work is for the animals and not for humans” protests to Madrusin, a born, 42 years old carrier, which works three decades since leaving the school on the Kawah Ijen.
It is able to carry as far as 110 kg and insured that he continues, “so long it goes”, because he needs the money for the education of his three children at the age between 10 and 18 years.
I will go not into pension, I will die here, because the volcano was my whole life.
Even if the sulfur burns the throat and it itches the eyes if the wind suddenly turns and gets jammed the mine workers in the thick columns, which ascend from the crater, the men are so hard that nobody complains about serious diseases… naturally except the usual breathing problems, arthritis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders, which deformed from the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on its back Unainik is with its 53 years only more able to carry 50 kg.
Break each day it and its companions 15 tons sulfur from the volcano, which are transported by three trucks over a goat path between the bushes to the camp in Tamansari in 18 kilometers distance.
“I will go not into pension, I will die here, because the volcano was my whole life” explains Unainik, whereby it opens its mouth far, in which some teeth is missing.
From its five children the oldest one works with its 30 years also as sulfur carrier.
The time passes, but the miserableness stops generation on generation in one of the hardest occupations of the world: that, which works as human load donkeys on the Kawah Ijen.
